abstract.para: The City of Seattle’s Cedar River Municipal Watershed is managed to support and supply clean drinking water to 1.6 million people in the greater Seattle area. The watershed covers 91,000 acres, hosts a rich diversity of plants, animals, and habitats, and is owned by the City of Seattle. In 2001 the City of Seattle prepared a multi-species Habitat Conservation Plan (HCP) to comply with the federal Endangered Species Act and to address a variety of related natural resource issues in the Cedar River Watershed. As defined in the HCP, the riparian zone is the area adjacent to surface waters and areas of high groundwater levels where the terrestrial system both influences, and is influenced by, the aquatic system. The City’s strategies for the riparian ecosystem are designed to protect the region’s supply of high-quality drinking water, to preserve and enhance stream and riparian ecosystems within the municipal watershed, and to restore and rehabilitate stream and riparian functions. This package includes as-builts from riparian restoration projects and their associated monitoring data.

The data is a result of monitoring that occurred after installation of riparian restoration projects in the Cedar River Municipal Watershed. The monitoring data includes plant survivorship but varies by project in what information was collected. The monitoring data was collected by multiple people over many years. Some projects were monitored for several years after project installation and some projects were monitored only once. Some projects included experimental plantings that were assigned a variety of treatments to test the efficacy of different planting strategies. In this instance, the monitoring data can be used to identify the success of the various strategies. Monitoring tabular data will be updated as more restoration projects are installed, and as previously installed projects receive continued monitoring.

description.para: Webster Creek, 2001: browse control experiment; tested 3 browse control types to determine most effective; types: mesh vexar tubing, translucent tree cones, and no browse control.

Webster Creek, 2010: experiment to determine best methods for establishing Thuja plicata. Variables included clearing understory in planting circles and leaving understory uncleared, adding wire cages for browse control and leaving some trees unprotected, and using small and large seedling sizes.

Webster Creek, 2012: experiment to test best browse control methods for establishing Thuja plicata. Variables included plastic cages, planting Thuja plicata in the same hole as Picea sitchensis, and providing no browse control.
Webster Creek, 2014: cleared understory in 30' diameter planting circles; planted some Thuja plicata and Picea sitchensis in the same hole.
Webster Creek, 2015: cleared understory in 30' diameter planting circles; planted some Thuja plicata and Picea sitchensis in the same hole.
Webster Creek, 2016: cleared understory in 2' diameter planting circles.
Webster Creek, 2017: cleared understory in 30' diameter planting circles.
Rock Creek, 2004: replanted site disturbance in skyline corridors used to install instream large woody debris.
Rock Creek, 2005: replanted site disturbance after installed instream large woody debris.

Taylor Creek, 2003: 3 sites, each with a unique treatment. One site along mainstem cleared understory in planting circles. Two sites along Middle Fork Taylor Creek: one project thinned dense young Abies grandis, one site girdled and felled Alnus rubra to release conifers.
Taylor Creek, 2009: cleared understory in 30' diameter planting circles.
Upper Cedar River, 2008 and 2009: cleared understory to release conifers; underplanted conifers in areas of little understory.
Upper Cedar River, 2011: underplanted low floodplain, lower than areas planted in 2008 to maximize future large woody debris recruitment to stream.

abstract.para: This project is a combination of Riparian Thinning and Riparian Conifer Underplanting projects implemented under the Cedar River Habitat Conservation Plan. The projects merged to form the Riparian Restoration project.

The current Riparian Restoration project continues the objectives of these former projects by reestablishing conifers and a diversity of hardwoods in riparian and streamside areas to help accelerate the restoration of diverse and structurally complex riparian stands within the watershed. The highest priority riparian restoration projects will be those in recently disturbed riparian zones that are currently vegetated but have a species composition that is not typical of such sites and does not contribute to healthy, natural riparian function. Adaptive management is used to ensure project objectives are met.
